// AttachmentPriority records the QoS classification of an attachment bundle.
// Each value maps 1:1 onto `peat_protocol::qos::QoSClass`:
//
//	BULK     → QoSClass::Bulk     (P5) — opportunistic; aging-eligible source
//	LOW      → QoSClass::Low      (P4) — intermediate aging tier
//	ROUTINE  → QoSClass::Normal   (P3) — default
//	PRIORITY → QoSClass::High     (P2) — preempts BULK/LOW once PRD-004 lands
//	CRITICAL → QoSClass::Critical (P1) — preempts everything once PRD-004 lands
//
// All five tiers (including LOW/P4) are exposed because peat-protocol's
// aging-promotion path is `Bulk → Low → Normal` (sync_queue.rs:118-119);
// collapsing P4 out of the wire surface would skip the intermediate aging
// tier or silently drop the aging promotion.
//
// v1-honesty: peat-node records the classification on the distribution
// document and uses it for ordering within its own queues, but does NOT
// enforce wire-level preemption between classes — a CRITICAL bundle will
// not actually pause an in-flight BULK transfer in v1. Cross-class
// preemption requires PRD-004 (Bandwidth Allocation to Sync Transport).
